Movie stunt man and coordinator '''Nick Gillard''', famously known as "'''The Swordsmaster'''," is best known now as the stunt coordinator for the ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[prequel trilogy]]. He had a minor role in [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Revenge of the Sith'']] as [[Jedi Master]] [[Cin Drallig]] (his [[Tuckerization|name]] spelled backward minus the k, though he is uncredited with this in the Episode III credits) and was [[Mark Hamill]]'s first choice as his stunt double for [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']].

Among Gillard's movie credits are various [[Wikipedia:James Bond|James Bond]] films, the original ''[[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|Star Wars]]'', the [[1989]] film ''[[Wikipedia:Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade|Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade]]'', the [[1991]] film ''[[Wikipedia:Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves|Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves]]'', the [[1993]] film ''[[Wikipedia:The Three Musketeers (1993 film)|The Three Musketeers]]'' and the [[1999]] film ''[[Wikipedia:Sleepy Hollow (film)|Sleepy Hollow]]'' (with [[Ray Park]]). He has also performed and coordinated for Lucas' ''[[Wikipedia:The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles|The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles]]'' television show.

==Biography==
During production of [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']], animation director [[Rob Coleman]] was attempting to figure out how to create the [[lightsaber duel]] between [[Yoda]] and [[Count]] [[Dooku]]. To do this, Coleman went to Gillard who was training with the actors [[Hayden Christensen]], [[Ewan McGregor]], and [[Christopher Lee]]. They talked about how a combatant would fight with small [[weapon]]s, and they looked at real-world examples.<ref name="Clones at 20">{{SW|url=news/clones-at-20-rob-coleman-interview|text=''Clones'' at 20 &#124; Rob Coleman on Bringing Yoda, Dexter Jettster, and More to Digital Life}}</ref>

As [[Kit Fisto]]'s [[lightsaber]] [[Lightsaber hilt|hilt]] was a personal favorite of Gillard, [[Cin Drallig's lightsaber]] hilt resembles Fisto's. Based on behind-the-scenes materials, his lightsaber blade was originally to be rotoscoped in [[Color|yellow]]. However, [[George Lucas]] would only allow either blue or green as the color of any regular [[Jedi]]'s lightsaber blade, with the exception of [[Samuel L. Jackson]]'s violet lightsaber blade he used as [[Mace Windu]]. Lucas would go no further with other colors, so Gillard chose green. However, a promotional image (appearing on [[Cin Drallig/Legends|Cin Drallig's Legends page]]) shows him with a blue lightsaber.

He claims to be able to speak and understand [[Binary|Droidspeak]] and is still offering [[Jedi training]] lessons similar to the ones he used to train the prequel cast as shown on his official site.

